\f16\fs24 \cf14 Type clock (\uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16 ): counts consecutive months the SSH SERVICE is active\
  Resets only when: the honeypot turns off for at least one month\
  Persona changes do NOT reset it\
\
Persona clock (\uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 \u7510 
\f16 ): counts consecutive months a SPECIFIC IDENTITY is visible\
  Resets when: the persona changes to any different persona\
  The type clock keeps running regardless\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This means persona rotation is cheap \'97 it resets \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 \u7510 
\f16  without affecting \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16 , costs one \uc0\u916 
\f5 \uc0\u8346 
\f16  churn slot, and requires only a configuration change (new hostname, new AD account, new certificate). Type rotation is expensive \'97 it is the only way to reset \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16 , costs one \uc0\u916  churn slot, requires taking the honeypot offline and reconfiguring the service implementation, and leaves a coverage gap while the honeypot is down.\
The solver exploits this asymmetry. It rotates personas frequently (cheap, effective against identity mapping) and rotates types only when necessary (expensive, required only when behavioral fingerprinting becomes the threat).\
