\f16\fs24 \cf14 \uc0\u961 
\f5 \cf14 \uc0\u8344 \u8336 
\f13 \cf14 \uc0\u739 
\f16  = 1.0 (typical setting)\
\
If threat intelligence reports \uc0\u961 \u960  = 0.95 (very high):\
  \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  = 3 \'d7 (1 \uc0\u8722  0.95/1.0) = 3 \'d7 0.05 = 0.15 months \u8776  5 days\
\
This is aggressive but finite. The solver interprets this as:\
"rotate approximately every week." Operationally demanding\
but not impossible.\
\
If \uc0\u961 \u960  somehow reaches exactly 1.0:\
  \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  = 3 \'d7 (1 \uc0\u8722  1.0/1.0) = 0\
\
At this point \uc0\u961 
\f5 \cf14 \uc0\u8344 \u8336 
\f13 \cf14 \uc0\u739 
\f16  serves as a clamp. The solver enforces\
\uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  \uc0\u8805  1 as a hard minimum \'97 you must always have at least\
one slot between rotations, because zero-slot rotation is\
impossible.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 A more conservative \uc0\u961 
\f5\b0 \uc0\u8344 \u8336 
\f6\b \uc0\u739 
\f17  setting:
\f16\b0 \
Some organizations set \uc0\u961 
\f5 \uc0\u8344 \u8336 
\f13 \uc0\u739 
\f16  = 0.80, which ensures \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  never drops below \uc0\u964 
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f20 \uc0\u8304 
\f16  \'d7 (1 \uc0\u8722  1.0/0.8). This prevents the formula from producing degenerate results even when threat intelligence reports unrealistically high probabilities.\
