\f17\b \cf0 Why it matters:
\f16\b0  An attacker who knows that certain techniques go undetected will specifically use those techniques. If T1048 is not covered by any honeypot, an attacker can exfiltrate data disguised as HTTPS traffic and walk out undetected. T tells the solver which attack behaviors remain in the blind spot so it can prioritize covering them.\

\f17\b T is also where ATT&CK differs from attack paths (G). G describes the route through the network \'97 which zone the attacker enters, which zone they pivot through, which zone their target is in. T describes what specific action they take at each step along that route. You need both: the route tells you where to put honeypots, the technique tells you which honeypot type can actually catch the attacker at that location.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

