\cf0 The weight formula combines these: a honeypot protecting oracle-prod at hop 1 earns 3.5 / 1 = 3.5 units of weight. The same honeypot at hop 3 earns only 3.5 / 3 = 1.17 units. This is the mathematical encoding of a simple security truth \'97 stopping an attacker before they reach the target is worth far more than catching them after they arrive.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 Why it matters:
\f16\b0  Without A, the solver cannot calculate what catching an attacker is actually worth. It would treat all detection events as equally valuable. A makes the solver prefer zones with high-value, close-to-entry assets \'97 which is exactly where experienced security teams put their best sensors.\
\
Z = \{\
  DMZ,       \'97 internet-facing, highest attack exposure\
  Internal,  \'97 office network, lateral movement hub\
  Cloud,     \'97 AWS-hosted, mixed trust\
  OT,        \'97 industrial systems, physically isolated\
  Management \'97 network infrastructure, highest privilege\
\}\
\

\f17\b Why the zones are structural, not just labels:
\f16\b0 \
Zone boundaries enforce three real constraints on what the solver can do:\
First, 
\f17\b air gaps.
\f16\b0  The OT zone is physically isolated from the DMZ and Cloud zones. There is no network cable connecting them. The solver cannot place a web_trap in the OT zone because the web_trap needs to receive HTTP connections from the internet, and the internet cannot reach OT. No matter how valuable such a deployment would theoretically be, the physical wire does not exist.\
Second, 
\f17\b eligibility.
\f16\b0  The scada_trap speaks industrial protocols \'97 Modbus, DNP3, OPC-UA. These protocols only exist in the OT zone. Deploying a scada_trap in the Cloud zone would be like putting a deep-sea diving suit in a shopping mall \'97 nobody there has any reason to interact with it.\
Third, 
\f17\b per-zone budgets.
\f16\b0  The OT team and the network security team have separate budget lines. B_\{OT\} = 2,000 units per month. Even if the global budget B has unused room, the solver cannot spend more than 2,000 in OT. A second scada_trap (cost 2.0) is blocked not because the global budget is exhausted but because the zone sub-limit is fully consumed.\

\f17\b How zones shape the solver's decisions:
\f16\b0 \
The five zones create a structured search space. The solver does not evaluate every possible host \'97 it evaluates every possible (honeypot type, zone) pair. An 8-type \'d7 5-zone space gives 40 combinations per time slot. Most of these are immediately eliminated by eligibility rules (scada_trap only in OT), air-gap constraints (no web_trap in OT), and budget limits (no second scada_trap when B_\{OT\} is spent). What remains is a small, well-constrained problem that RC2 can solve to certified optimality in seconds.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 How K, T, A, Z fit together\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f16\b0 \cf0 These four sets define the skeleton of the problem before a single deployment decision is made:\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f10\fs22 \cf13 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f16\fs24 \cf14 K tells the solver: here are your tools\
T tells the solver: here is what each tool can catch\
A tells the solver: here is what you are protecting and how much each asset is worth\
Z tells the solver: here is the terrain and where each tool is allowed to operate\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Together they constrain the search space from the theoretical maximum \'97 any honeypot, anywhere, detecting anything \'97 down to a small set of feasible, meaningful deployments that fit the actual network and actual budget. Everything else in the formulation (attack paths, constraints, persona layer) operates on top of this skeleton.\
\
===== \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f17\b\fs28 \cf0 Attack Picture \'97 G, \uc0\u961 , iv\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f16\b0\fs24 \cf0 These three parameters answer one question: 
\f17\b what does the solver know about the enemy before it starts planning?
\f16\b0 \
Without G, \uc0\u961 , and iv, the solver would treat all honeypot placements as equally valuable. An SSH trap in a quiet management subnet would be worth the same as an SSH trap sitting directly on the path an attacker takes to reach the database. These three parameters are what make the solver care about 
\f23\i where
\f16\i0  attackers go, 
\f23\i how often
\f16\i0  they go there, and 
\f23\i how much
\f16\i0  it costs the defender to miss them at each step.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
