\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 Why conflicts exist \'97 three real reasons:
\f16\b0 \

\f17\b Reason 1 \'97 Shared monitoring pipeline.
\f16\b0  Two honeypots that capture the same attacker behavior flood the same logging system with duplicate alerts. The monitoring team cannot tell the signals apart. What looks like doubled coverage is actually doubled noise with no additional detection value.\

\f17\b Reason 2 \'97 Shared physical infrastructure.
\f16\b0  Some honeypot types require the same network tap, the same monitoring server, or the same logging database. Running both simultaneously overloads the shared resource and degrades the quality of both.\

\f17\b Reason 3 \'97 Contradictory network signals.
\f16\b0  Two honeypots presenting conflicting identities on the same network segment can confuse each other's deception. An attacker scanning the network sees inconsistent behavior and correctly infers that something artificial is present.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
C = \{\
  (generic_trap, dns_trap),    \'97 both capture T1046 network scanning;\
                                 running both saturates the same SIEM\
                                 alert queue without additional coverage\
\
  (web_trap, generic_trap),    \'97 both expose HTTP services; generic_trap\
                                 mimics web behavior and creates ambiguous\
                                 signals when web_trap is also present\
\
  (smb_trap, generic_trap),    \'97 both capture T1021 SMB lateral movement;\
                                 duplicate signals confuse incident response\
\}\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 How C works in the constraint:
\f16\b0 \
The constraint C4 says: for every conflicting pair (k
\f13 \uc0\u7522 
\f16 , k
\f5 \uc0\u8343 
\f16 ) in C, at most one of them can be active in any given time slot t, across any zone and any persona.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Month 1 scenario: The solver wants to deploy generic_trap in Internal\
                  AND dns_trap in DMZ simultaneously.\
\
C4 blocks this: (generic_trap, dns_trap) 
\f4 \uc0\u8712 
\f16  C\
                x_\{generic, t=1\} = 1 forces x_\{dns, t=1\} = 0\
                The dns_trap cannot run in month 1 at all.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The solver must choose one. It calculates which earns more credit \'97 dns_trap covering T1572 Protocol Tunneling (\uc0\u963 =0.85, rare and stealthy) versus generic_trap covering T1046 Network Scanning (\u963 =0.20, common and already caught by other means) \'97 and picks the dns_trap. The generic_trap stays off that month.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 Why this matters for the budget result:
\f16\b0 \
At XLarge scale, the solver uses only approximately 0.1% of the global budget B. This is not a modeling error. It is a direct consequence of C. Conflict constraints prevent the solver from stacking up redundant honeypots. After deploying the four most complementary types (ssh_trap, db_trap, dns_trap, ad_trap), adding a fifth type either conflicts with one of the four or produces redundant technique coverage. The solver correctly recognizes that the fifth deployment earns less credit than it costs and leaves the remaining budget unspent. C is what makes the portfolio sparse and targeted rather than maximal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
