\cf0 This single formula encodes a profound operational insight. Let us compute it for three specific scenarios:\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f10\fs22 \cf13 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f16\fs24 \cf14 Scenario A: ssh_trap near oracle-prod at hop 3\
  \uc0\u119 \u771  = 0.75 \'d7 3.5 / 3 = 0.875\
\
Scenario B: ssh_trap near a workstation at hop 2\
  \uc0\u119 \u771  = 0.75 \'d7 1.0 / 2 = 0.375\
\
Scenario C: web_trap near web01 at hop 1\
  \uc0\u119 \u771  = 0.55 \'d7 1.5 / 1 = 0.825\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Scenario A covers the most critical asset (oracle-prod, d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f16 =3.5) but at hop 3. Scenario C covers a less critical asset (web server, d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f16 =1.5) but at hop 1. They end up with similar values (0.875 vs 0.825) because the perimeter advantage of hop 1 nearly offsets the lower asset criticality. The formula automatically balances criticality against proximity to entry.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 Why dividing by h
\f6 \uc0\u7496 
\f17  is the right choice:
\f16\b0 \
Imagine the web-to-database attack path \uc0\u960 
\f20 \uc0\u8321 
\f16 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
Hop 1 \'97 DMZ web server:\
  Attacker has entered through the web portal.\
  No internal data accessed yet.\
  Catching here = full prevention.\
  Damage prevented: 100% of the potential breach.\
\
Hop 2 \'97 Internal LAN:\
  Attacker has crossed the DMZ and is moving through\
  the internal network. They have conducted reconnaissance.\
  Catching here = prevent database breach but not\
  the initial perimeter compromise.\
  Damage prevented: roughly 70% of the potential breach.\
\
Hop 3 \'97 Oracle database:\
  Attacker has reached the database. They may have\
  already run queries. Catching here = forensic evidence\
  but the database was accessible.\
  Damage prevented: roughly 30% \'97 attribution only.\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Dividing by h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  makes the value at hop 1 three times the value at hop 3, which roughly matches the actual damage-prevention ratio. The formula is not perfectly calibrated \'97 no formula could be \'97 but it is in the right direction and the right order of magnitude.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f17\b \cf0 The combined effect of d
\f5\b0 \uc0\u8344 
\f17\b  and h
\f6 \uc0\u7496 
\f17  \'97 a full worked example:
\f16\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
The solver is deciding between two placements:\
\
Option 1: db_trap near oracle-prod in the DB subnet\
  Asset: oracle-prod, d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f16  = 3.5, h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  = 3\
  Technique: T1213 data collection, w = 0.80\
  \uc0\u119 \u771  = 0.80 \'d7 3.5 / 3 = 0.933\
\
Option 2: ssh_trap near the DMZ web server\
  Asset: web01, d
\f5 \uc0\u8344 
\f16  = 1.5, h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  = 1\
  Technique: T1021 lateral movement, w = 0.75\
  \uc0\u119 \u771  = 0.75 \'d7 1.5 / 1 = 1.125\
\
Option 2 wins despite protecting a less critical asset,\
because its perimeter position (h
\f13 \uc0\u7496 
\f16  = 1) more than\
compensates for the lower asset criticality.\
\
This is the perimeter-preference principle encoded in math.\
A good honeypot at the front door beats a great honeypot\
at the vault \'97 because the front-door honeypot catches\
the attacker before they reach the vault at all.\
